

<section xml:id="ACh4Sec3DiagonalizingMatricies">
  <title>Diagonalisering van matrikse</title>
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Ons sÃª dat 'n <m>n \times n</m>-matriks <m>\mat{A}</m> is
        <term>diagonaliseerbaar</term>
        as daar 'n inverteerbare <m>n \times n</m>-matriks
        <m>\mat{P}</m> bestaan sodat <m>\mat{P}^{-1} \mat{A} \mat{P}</m> 'n
        diagonaalmatriks is.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <m>\mat{A} = \cmatrix{ 2 \amp  1 \\ \frac{1}{2} \amp  \frac{5}{2} }</m>
        is diagonaliseerbaar, want as
        <me>
          \mat{P} = \cmatrix{-2 \amp  1 \\ 1 \amp  1}
        </me>
        dan
        <me>
          \mat{P}^{-1} = -\frac{1}{3} \cmatrix{1 \amp  -1 \\ -1 \amp  -2}
        </me>
        en ons gaan na,
        <md>
          <mrow>\mat{P}^{-1} \mat{A} \mat{P} \amp = -\frac{1}{3} {\cmatrix{1 \amp  -1\\ -1 \amp  -2}} {\cmatrix{2 \amp  1\\ \frac{1}{2} \amp  \frac{5}{3}}} {\cmatrix{ -2 \amp  1\\ 1 \amp  1}}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = - \frac{1}{3} {\cmatrix{ \frac{3}{2} \amp  - \frac{3}{2}\\ -3 \amp  -6}} {\cmatrix{-2 \amp  1\\ 1 \amp  1}}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = - \frac{1}{3} {\cmatrix{ - \frac{9}{2} \amp  0\\ 0 \amp  -9}}</mrow>
          <mrow>= {\cmatrix{\frac{3}{2} \amp  0\\ 0 \amp  3}}</mrow>
        </md>
        wat wel 'n diagonaalmatriks is.
        Meer hieroor volg in die tweede semester!
        Vir nou is dit al wat jy moet weet.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

